title: For Sale:  Speer Gold Dot 245 Rounds 124 +P
postcontent:
I received a box of this in trade. It is a white box marked Not for LE Use, Practice ammuntition. It was sold at Fin, Feather and Fur for $130.

I will trade for 200 rounds of Winchester Ranger-T 147 gr
I will sell for $90 FTF Akron

Here is the explanation of the source of the ammo:

Guys, this is a Law Enforcement contract overrun. Federal HST, Winchester Ranger Bonded, and now Speer Gold Dot have all found their way to retail channels in this manner. It says not for LE use because it's it's supposed to be for the contract order and since the contract buyer is not taking them it is only to be used in retail channels and not used in any other contract or by any other agency. Each contract has a specific requirement they ask for in the order. The manufacturer would like to not risk an LEO using this round and having it be outside the department requirements and the blame going to the manufacturer for such a round being outside the department requirements for a duty load. There is absolutely nothing wrong with it. The "Not for LE use" sticker is a save your butt liability sticker, so that if an LEO uses the round in a shoot, and after investigation it is deemed the ammo falls outside the very specific department requirements for velocity, they won't be liable for any damages because it was marked to not be used in that capacity.

title: For Sale:  RARE Smith & Wesson 6944 DAO 9mm
postcontent: Wow...now this is a very rare Smith & Wesson - the 6944 9mm DAO. Showing signs of holster wear only but otherwise in top notch condition with no scratches, nicks or gouges of any kind. The 6944 is a very unique S&W for certain - only 512 were produced; yes, only 512 in existence. It's built on the 69x 3rd generation platform using parts from the 669 and 69xx series. It's intended as a DAO but in reality, it's a .5 DAO. The Slide must be racked to half-cock the Hammer and the trigger will not fully cock the Hammer in any way. Very unique and rare pistol. You just won't see another in a long, long time. This pistol includes 4 12-Round Magazines and a used Smith & Wesson 69xx Series Leather Holster.

I've installed Warren Tactical sights, a custom stippled backstrap (as well as the original two, a small and a medium), an extended mag release (I'll include the original as well), and a very nice Apex DC-AEK trigger that fixes the mushy weird trigger that plagues the M&P (also including all the spare parts from that). I also replaced the gen 1 striker w/ the latest model from S&W. I would be willing to trade w/ it a nice CompTac kydex OWB paddle holster and the eight mags that I have, 3 of which have the arredondo extensions on them for extra happy time. It's in great condition, I'm a little OCD about cleaning and care.

It's a great gun, and a fun project. I sometimes think I enjoy building the things more than shooting, and need a new project. :P

title: For Sale:  Tangodown Advanced Combat Bipod (ACB-4) in Flat Dark Earth
postcontent:
I got this for a rifle I ended up never using it on. It is out of the packaging, but this bipod is in excellent/like new condition. I'm asking $155 shipped. This bipod retails for $190 to $220.

The Advanced Combat Bipod features the following:

    Low Profile Design
    Built-in Cant and Traverse
    Silent Leg Release Mechanism
    Adjustable Legs

Standard Height: 8"
Fully Extended: 10 1/2"
Weight: 16 1/3 oz

Advanced combat bipod is designed specifically for the M16/M4 weapon families. Attached directly to the MIL-STD 1913 MWS (SOPMOD) rail system, no separate adapters necessary.

Bipod body - The clamp body and center portion are forged from 7075-T6 aluminum with Type III hard anodizing. The center portion has two pivots, to which the legs are attached. It will fit on any MIL-STD 1913 rail, using a clamp on the base that is secured by two stainless, black finish screws. An allen wrench or screwdriver can be used to install or remove the ACB. A black stainless button on the outside of each pivot releases and engages a sealed, pre-lubricated stainless steel locking mechanism, which allows the bipod legs to rotate 90° from stowed to deployed. It is locked in both positions and can only be released by puching the button. The center portion rotates for traversing and allows about 40° of angle. The whole bipod body can cant 15°. Urethane bushings keep the bipod center-favoured while allowing it to cant on uneven ground.

Legs - The legs are made up of two pieces - the inner and outer legs. The outer legs house the locking mechanism and button, and have 3 holes/detents which provide 3 height adjustments. The outer legs are made of a proprietary glass-reinforced nylon and are much tougher than they look (I was concerned early on in the design stage when I saw the inner legs, but tried to snap one and I couldn't. The ACB-4 has exceeded Army drop-test requirements). The inner legs are made of carbon-fiber reinforced nylon, and slide in and out of the outer legs. At the top of the inner leg is a button, which fits into the detents in the outer legs. The inner legs are extended by simply pulling them out. In order to shorten them, the button must be depressed and the leg slid in, where the button will engage the next detent. The feet are large to prevent sinking in sand and aggressively checkered for a good grip. When stowed, the bipod legs are locked along the rail system, fitting neatly between the lower and side rails.

postcontent:
This is a Polytech MAK-90 7.62x39mm post ban with Thumbhole Stock. Chinese milspec stamped receiver (thicker than standard stamped aks).  Comes with (1) issued POLYtech 30rd. mag chromed follower and POLY-China floorplate, (1) 30rd. (unknown manufacture) but good quality mag, broken shell extractor kit, issued Chi-Com green sling, and Romanian made NEW 75rd DRUM! This was bought new-unfired year ago and has only been fire on one recent occasion then cleaned and put away. It's only been field stripped once and has very lever markings from safety and gas tube typical to AKs. Please no low ball offers. I have done my homework and I know what it's worth. I suggest you do the same before making an offer. This is great as a collectors piece or a shooter. Would only conside a trade for an AR-15 plus cash (depending on what you have)

One more thing that really isn't that import to some but to others is everything. The BATF banned the importation of AK 47 barrels from any contry and any arms imported from China years ago and just about every AK 47 or AK 74 you run across these days is a parts kit built on a US made receiver. If it's not done right you will end up with problems...Century Arms is famous for questionable built AKs. The Polytech AK 47s on the other hand were completely built in China as as export model...semi-automatic rifle instead of full auto. So there isn't really any question about how well they work. Also most newer built AK 47 kits are not going to have a chrome lined barrel. The polytechs on the other hand came with factory chromed barrel like milspec AR-15s which adds to the demand. Bottom line, they don't make or import these anymore and if you want a higher quality build than most Aks the this is for you.
